“Beauty is Mona Lisa” 6x6 270$ •
•Dec 2nd Tiny Treasure is the epitome of beauty as defined by an iconic image of the Mona Lisa. Referencing this female image places her power front and centre. Although this painting of her is small in size- it has a big impact. Millions have made the journey to see this painting in the Louvre in Paris. And I’m sure it’s millions because if you have ever visited this painting you will experience the crowds of people taking pictures of it. It’s quite remarkable. Sometimes art can make an affect.

It’s time to rock it and get a small piece for that someone special! Everyday a small piece will be released until Dec 25th. Always good to have a little bit of a sneak 🫣 peek. •

“Dream of Jeannie” 6x6 270$•

Inspired by the 1960s tv show I Dream of Jeannie, An american fantasy sitcom TV series, that starred Barbara Eden, this series is about a genie in a bottle who marries an astronaut. Sounds crazy, but was entertaining. Jeannie often played her magic to get her way. This series reflected the time when women were restless. The character of Jeannie was between the traditional roles that women had played but had the pre-feminist rumblings of the 1960s. Her character constantly tried to redefine her role as the "slave wife".•
•
•
•#idreamofjeannie #smallart #artasgifts #1960stv

“Wild with Janis Joplin” 6x6 270$•
•
•Inspired by an image of motorcycle tough girl and singer Janis Joplin. Her rise to stardom in the late 1960s was parallel with the rise of the feminist movement. She served as an unconscious symbol for young women and her hippie style reflected the wild, liberated look at that time. She personified the the brave, culture disruption that was happening in the American culture of the 1960s-70s. Yet her expressive gender bending persona was ahead of her time. This freedom in understanding and expressing ones own sexuality and using it as part of her image was unique for that time but is now a norm. Janis was a true pioneer •
•
•
•#janisjoplin #smallart #giftart

“Call of the Wild” 6x6 $270•
•

It's cowgirl time with Annie Oakley! Annie was an American sharpshooter that performed with the Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show in the elate 1800s. With her independent ideology and her sharp shooting skills, Annie demonstrated that women did not have to be limited by their gender. Aside from her performing, Annie trained over 15,000 women on how to shoot a gun. Annie believed in the power of  independence and self definition. Using her sharp shooting skills, she challenged stereotypes and made the cowgirl a powerful image. •
•
•#annieoakley #cowgirl #westernart

“Reach the Unreachable” (tinker bell) 12x12 $350
•
•As her name suggests, Tinker Bell is an inventor. She works to helps fairies with their creations and pushes for change. At first glance, one would not think that Tinker Bell is a positive image. The reality is that her character is one of independence, non-romantic, not a princess and has an active speaking role. Notably, Tinker Bell encourages change, especially for the female role in technology. A modern  interpretation of a character that just isn’t a fairy. •
•
•#tinkerbell #disney #fairies #artgift #originalart

“Stand Up” 6x6 $270•
•
•An image of the iconic Nina Simone, this piece speaks to her vision and her persistent use of her art as protest music. Known as the “High Priestess of Soul”, Simone was dedicated to civil rights and activism. Although she has encouraged and spoke on the strength within black women, her music crosses racial lines and has been adopted by women who have recognized her powerful art. •
•
•#ninasimone #giftart

It never gets old for me when a client sends me a pic of a piece in there final resting place. It’s a thrill and an honor. #whatawonderfulworld

It’s been a year of travel, showing art, selling art and looking at art. There is nothing like exploring the wold and making a living at the same time. A good way to live. •
•The core  to this lifestyle are my collectors. Without those who love art, and buy art, there would not be the opportunity to bring art to different communities throughout the US. Thank you.

It’s been a week away from it all. A time to reflect and realize that 2023 is about “calm” and “acceptance “. Being in a space where it’s good to activate-to create- but to let life take you in its dance. •
•
•Taking time to reflect is a way to reassess. To evaluate whether the challenges we take on is what makes us happy.•
•
•If you haven’t done it yet- take a moment to reflect on what and how life should be. So often we just keep going without stopping to register. •
•It’s time to stop. To be. Accept and be calm.

“Come to Me” 36x36•
•A perfect piece beckoning a dream. Inspired by a Pan Am ad with two business men arriving- this piece brings to mind the creaminess of yearning for love. •
•Visualize love and it will come your way.

“Sun of my Smile” 36x36•

Inspired by a vintage postcard of a motel from the 1960s. Blended with the text  of the poem Phenomenal Woman by Maya Angelou, a vintage ad for Oil with the phrase Time for Change and a beautiful vintage car on its way to paradise. This piece brings together the story of a place of inspiration and nostalgia. •
•Telling a story with images is all about letting the images play into each other. The car driving into the distance brings to mind a place to escape to. •
•
With the grey weather- all I can think of is where I want to escape to. Where would you like to go? •

“America’s Jewels” 36x36•
•
•I love Westerns. There is something about these movies from the 1950s:60s that have a ruggedness and fearlessness. Women in these films have  pioneer spirit but they are often depicted without guns. Often they are depicted as a virgin or whore. But sometimes there is a female character that steps out of the norm and becomes an active character. Films like The Cattle Queen of Montana (1954) with Barbara Stanwyck is a perfect example. A role where a woman can take care of herself. •
•
•

•
•A few weeks ago I was on vacation and a Congo line began in a bar I was hanging out in. Congo lines are a strange thing. A group of people who don’t know each other begin to dance and follow each other. A group celebrating a moment. •
•
•There aren’t many acts that people do as groups that collectively celebrate a moment. •
•
•When was the last time you were in a Congo line? •

“Thirst for Life” 36x36•
•
•So often we take our partners for granted. The daily grind of life can anesthetize us to the beauty and small ways that the people in our life make things so much better. •

•
•And then there is a moment, a conversation, an instance of nurturing- a recognition that this person sees me, loves me- and this is the reason he is my Valentine. •

….Now you understand

“Time for Change” 36x36•
•
Sometimes we move forward in life, by looking back from where we came from.

The Ferris wheel of our future becomes a place we keep trying to get onto.

This past week I spent a few days with my young adult daughter, and spent the time to just not think of the future, or the past, but to live in the present .

Because ultimately that’s all we have.

Going to the La Quinta art celebration that is this week. Come see this beautiful painting enjoy some art. booth 223 

@laquintaartcelebration #artfair #vintageart #originalart

“Elegant Ladies” 36x36• A piece that brings in #internationalwomensday full of life and independence! 
•
• Arriving at La Quinta California, I am about to set up @laquintaartcelebration today for the show for the next few days. It’s been a long drive from Florida, but it’s exciting to be in one of the best art fairs in the US! •
•
•Here’s to hoping the sun will shine over the next few days! •
•I’m at #booth 223 in case you are in the Palm Springs CA area!

“Time to Roll” 36x36•
•
•Feeling the angst as I begin my looong drive home. It’s been a few weeks of shows and travel. A great time to chat about art, look at art, and sell art. The last two shows; @coconutgroveartsfestival and @laquintaartcelebration were more than about selling art. It was about meeting other artists, talking about our goals and obstacles and being in an industry that’s purpose is to make people think and make the world just a little bit more beautiful. How do we do this? •
•For me- it’s not about the decoration and I pretty object. It’s about thinking. Contemplating and celebrating a moment brought on by a memory. When this happens my purpose has been fulfilled. •
•
•

•
•Do you ever wait for a “sign”; an indication that you are on the right track? This is a a piece about the listening and watching for that guiding sign. 
•
•As I drive back to Toronto, I have lots of time to reflect on the past few weeks driving from coast to coast showing my work. It’s amazing how many great conversations I had with people who love art and stories. •
•
•It are these exchanges that remind me how art brings out 
our common shared views of life. 
••
•It’s pretty amazing how art can create a space where we get a sense and a deeper understanding of things that we just can take for granted

“Be in the Moment” 36x36 original •
•
•So often we plan for the future. We look towards being in another place and when we get there- we think happiness will abound. •
•
•Perhaps the goal should be to revel in the moment. To register the warmth of the day, the sun shining bright or really just waking up everyday feeling full of energy. That is a moment of happiness •
•
•This weekend I will be showing this beautiful piece about being in the moment at @dogwoodfestival in Piedmont Park in Atlanta. Booth #189•
•

“One way to go” 36x36 •
•
•A piece inspired by a photo from the 1960s in Montgomery Alabama. The figures walking are for civil rights. Headlines along the crowd walking are from old Life Magazine articles such as “revolutionary” “for the good life” •
•
•Layers of tissue paper, vintage wallpapers, and paint creates an image of hope and inspiration. •
•Creating art that has some kind of political narrative without hitting the viewer over the head with the message is the goal with most of my work.•
•Yes they are beautiful paintings. 
•Yes this could be just another street scene. The reality is that the message is about moving forward. Moving towards a place that is equitable, just and respectful. •
•
•Now being shown @dogwoodfestival I #atlanta

social_posts.post_text:
This past weekend I showed this piece titled “liberation” at the Atlanta Art fair. A couple of young men (about 20 years old) stood and looked closely at the piece asking questions about its meaning. •
•
•I went into my spiel about it being about a woman looking for her future. That she is searching for her “liberation”•
•
• I then looked at them and said I’m sure they understood since they were feminists in their outlook. The best part is that they looked right back and said yes. They knew what it meant. •
•

“Day to Float” now available as  36x36 acrylic glass piece framed. 
•
Acquainted with the Night by Robert Frost •
•I have been one acquainted with the night. 
I have walked out in rain - and back in rain. 
I have outwalked the furthest city light. 

I have looked down the saddest city lane. 
I have passed by the watchman on his beat 
And dropped my eyes, unwilling to explain. 

I have stood still and stopped the sound of feet 
When far away an interrupted cry 
Came over houses from another street, 

But not to call me back or say good-bye; 
And further still at an unearthly height, 
One luminary clock against the sky 

Proclaimed the time was neither wrong nor right. 
I have been one acquainted with the night.•

It’s been a year of creating 40 large scale pieces and 50 smaller sized originals. A year where inspiration came from vintage postcards and stories of escape and travel. 

A year where friends, family and my beloved collectors kept supporting my life’s calling. 

When you keep to your passion- keep focusing on your core values- then I believe the universe will bring you abundance. 

Be bright, be positive, and be creative. 

Bring it on 2024!
